Phase 1, Lesson 1: The Terminal
Before you touch a single JavaScript file, you need to be comfortable in the terminal. Here's why: the terminal is the native language of every server, every deployment pipeline, and every senior engineer's workflow. GUIs (click-based interfaces) hide what's actually happening. The terminal shows you the truth.
The Analogy
Think of your computer's file system like a building. Your Finder/File Explorer is the elevator — it takes you places but you don't really understand the building. The terminal is the blueprint and the stairs. You know exactly where you are, how you got there, and what's around you.
The 10 Commands You Need Right Now
CommandWhat it doespwd"Where am I?" — prints your current directoryls"What's here?" — lists files/foldersls -laSame, but shows hidden files and permissionscd foldernameMove into a foldercd ..Go up one levelmkdir foldernameCreate a new foldertouch filename.jsCreate a new filerm filename.jsDelete a file (no trash can — it's gone)rm -rf foldernameDelete a folder and everything in it (be careful)clearClear the terminal screen
Your Git Setup (Do This Now)
Git is how you save your work professionally. Every change gets a "commit" — a snapshot with a message explaining what you did. Run these commands one at a time:
bashgit init
git config --global user.name "Britton"
git config --global user.email "your@email.com"
Then after you create your README:
bashgit add README.md
git commit -m "docs: initialize project roadmap and README"
That commit message follows a real convention called Conventional Commits. The format is type: description. Types include feat, fix, docs, refactor, chore. Seniors use this so the git history reads like a changelog, not a diary.

