Phase 1, Lesson 2: Git Branching
Here's why this matters before we write a single line of code.
The Analogy — Google Docs Version History
Imagine you're writing a big essay in Google Docs. The main document is called main — it's the clean, working version. Instead of editing the main doc directly and potentially breaking it, you make a copy called feature/add-introduction. You write in the copy, get it right, then merge it back into the main doc. If you mess up the copy, the main doc is untouched.
That's a branch. In professional teams, nobody ever commits directly to main. Every feature, every fix, every experiment gets its own branch.
bash# See what branch you're on right now
git branch

# Create a new branch and switch to it
git checkout -b feature/terminal-practice

# Confirm you switched
git branch
# The * shows your active branch
The branch naming convention follows the same logic as commits:

feature/ — new functionality
fix/ — bug fixes
chore/ — maintenance, no code change
docs/ — documentation only


