Phase 1, Lesson 3: Variables & Data Types
This is where JavaScript actually starts. Everything you build on the Fades & Facials site — the services list, the booking data, the admin panel — is built from these primitives.
The Analogy — Labeled Boxes
Your computer's memory is a giant warehouse of boxes. A variable is just a labeled box you can put a value in and find later.
javascriptlet chairsAvailable = 3       // a number box
const shopName = "Fades & Facials"  // a text box that never changes
let isOpen = true             // a yes/no box
let vs const — The One Rule You Need
javascriptconst shopName = "Fades & Facials"
shopName = "Bob's Cuts"  // 💥 ERROR — const boxes are sealed
javascriptlet chairsAvailable = 3
chairsAvailable = 2      // ✅ Fine — let boxes can be updated
The senior habit: use const by default. Only switch to let when you know the value will change. If you see let everywhere in a codebase, it's a sign someone didn't think carefully about their data.
The 4 Types You'll Use 90% of the Time
javascriptconst name = "Britton"        // String  — text, always in quotes
const age = 24                // Number  — any number, no quotes
const isLoggedIn = false      // Boolean — only true or false
const appointment = null      // Null    — intentionally empty

