Phase 1, Lesson 9: Scope & Closures
This is the last concept before we get into async code, and it's one that separates juniors from seniors.
Scope — Where a Variable Lives
javascriptconst shopName = "Fades & Facials"  // lives everywhere — global scope

function getGreeting() {
  const greeting = "Welcome"        // lives only inside this function
  return `${greeting} to ${shopName}`
}

console.log(getGreeting())  // works fine
console.log(greeting)       // 💥 ReferenceError — greeting doesn't exist out here
Think of scope like rooms in a building. A variable declared in a room can see everything in the hallway (outer scope). But the hallway can't see inside the room.
Closures — A Function That Remembers
This is the one that makes people's brains hurt, so I'll use a real example:
javascriptfunction makeCounter() {
  let count = 0             // this variable is trapped inside

  return function() {
    count = count + 1       // inner function can still see count
    return count
  }
}

const counter = makeCounter()
console.log(counter())  // 1
console.log(counter())  // 2
console.log(counter())  // 3
count should be gone after makeCounter() runs. But it isn't — because the inner function holds a reference to it. That inner function plus the variables it remembers is called a closure.
You'll use this pattern in the admin dashboard — for example, a function that tracks how many times a barber's profile has been viewed without exposing that count to the rest of the app.

