Phase 1, Lesson 10: Promises & Async/Await
The Analogy — Ordering at a Restaurant
You walk up to the counter and order a haircut. The barber doesn't freeze you in place while he finishes the client in the chair. He says "I'll call your name when I'm ready" and you go sit down. You're free to do other things — check your phone, talk to someone. When he's done, he calls you.
That's async code. JavaScript doesn't stop and wait — it says "go do this, and when it's done, here's what to run next."
The Old Way — Callbacks (just so you recognize them)
javascript// Don't write this — just recognize it
setTimeout(function() {
  console.log("Called after 2 seconds")
}, 2000)
The Modern Way — Async/Await
javascriptfunction wait(ms) {
  return new Promise((resolve) => setTimeout(resolve, ms))
}

async function bookAppointment(clientName) {
  console.log(`${clientName} is checking in...`)
  await wait(2000)
  console.log(`${clientName}'s appointment is confirmed`)
}

bookAppointment("Britton")
Two new keywords:
async before a function means it will do something that takes time.
await pauses that one function until the promise resolves — but the rest of your app keeps running. It's like the barber calling your name — you were paused waiting, but the shop kept operating.
Fetching Real Data — What You'll Do on the Barbershop Site
Every time your site loads services from a database, this is the pattern:
javascriptasync function getServices() {
  const response = await fetch("https://api.example.com/services")
  const data = await response.json()
  return data
}
fetch goes and gets data from a URL. It returns a Promise. await waits for it. .json() converts the raw response into a JavaScript object you can use. Also a Promise. Also awaited.

