What Just Happened — The Key Insight
Britton is checking in...
Source is checking in...
Britton — seat ready, come on in
Source — seat ready, come on in
Both started before either finished. JavaScript didn't wait for Britton to complete before starting Source. It fired both functions, hit the await in each one, said "I'll come back to these" and kept going. One second later, both finished almost simultaneously.
This is the event loop in action. JavaScript is single-threaded — it can only do one thing at a time — but await lets it park a task and work on something else while it waits. Both clients checked in at the same time, like two barbers working in parallel chairs.
If you had put await before the calls:
javascriptawait checkIn("Britton")  // waits fully before moving on
await checkIn("Source")   // only starts after Britton is done
Then it would run one at a time. No await on the calls = they run concurrently. This distinction will matter when you build the booking system.

Your Question — const wait vs function wait
Great question. Look at both:
javascript// Function declaration
function wait(ms) {
  return new Promise((resolve) => setTimeout(resolve, ms))
}

// Arrow function stored in a const
const wait = (ms) => new Promise((resolve) => setTimeout(resolve, ms))
They do the exact same thing. The difference is one we covered in Lesson 5 — hoisting.
A function declaration gets hoisted to the top of the file. You can call it before the line it's defined on and it works fine.
A const arrow function is not hoisted. If you try to call wait() before the line where you declared it, you get a ReferenceError.
For a helper like wait that's used right below where it's defined, either works. In practice, most modern codebases use const arrow functions for consistency. The important thing is picking one style and not mixing them randomly.

