Phase 1, Lesson 11: Error Handling
Every function you've written assumes things go right. Real code has to handle when they don't.
The Analogy — A Safety Net
A tightrope walker doesn't walk without a net. Your code shouldn't run without error handling. The net doesn't stop you from falling — it stops the fall from ending the whole show.
javascriptasync function getBooking(id) {
  try {
    const response = await fetch(`https://api.example.com/bookings/${id}`)
    const data = await response.json()
    return data
  } catch (error) {
    console.log("Booking fetch failed:", error.message)
    return null
  }
}
try — run this code. catch — if anything in the try block throws an error, come here instead of crashing.
Without the try/catch, one network failure crashes your entire app. With it, you handle the failure gracefully and decide what to do next.
Throwing Your Own Errors
javascriptfunction getServicePrice(serviceName) {
  const prices = { fade: 35, facial: 65 }
  
  if (!prices[serviceName]) {
    throw new Error(`Unknown service: ${serviceName}`)
  }
  
  return prices[serviceName]
}

try {
  const price = getServicePrice("manicure")
} catch (error) {
  console.log(error.message)  // "Unknown service: manicure"
}
throw stops the function immediately and sends the error to the nearest catch block.

