App Router vs Pages Router — 2 minutes
Pages Router (old, pre-Next.js 13):
Every file in pages/ became a route automatically. pages/services.js → /services. Simple, but it mixed server and client code awkwardly and had no good way to handle layouts without hacks.
App Router (current, Next.js 13+):
Routes live in app/. But instead of the file being the route, the folder is the route and a page.tsx inside it is what renders. Every component is a Server Component by default — meaning it renders on the server and ships zero JavaScript to the browser unless you explicitly opt into client-side behavior with "use client".
Why App Router for Fades & Facials specifically: the admin dashboard needs server-side auth checks. With App Router you can protect routes at the layout level without client-side flicker. The barber's login wall is airtight before the browser gets anything.

Global CSS placement
In App Router, app/layout.tsx is the root shell that wraps every single page. It's the one guaranteed file that always renders. So global CSS — resets, Tailwind base, font imports — gets imported once there and inherited everywhere. Importing it per-component would mean duplicated styles and specificity chaos.

Folder Structure for Your Three Routes
This is the pattern. Read it, understand it, then I'm going to make you extend it:
app/
├── layout.tsx          ← root shell, wraps everything
├── page.tsx            ← renders at /
├── services/
│   └── page.tsx        ← renders at /services
└── admin/
    └── page.tsx        ← renders at /admin
The folder name = the URL segment. The page.tsx inside = what the user sees. Anything else in that folder (components, utilities specific to that route) doesn't become a route unless it's named page.tsx.

